image.altText: a woman taking a selfie while standing on sand at a beach

props.synopsis: NSW Police suspend the use of bean-bag rounds, part of their arsenal for the past 10 years, after the death of Krista Kach. What exactly is the device also known as a super-sock round?

title.children: What are bean-bag rounds, the police weaponry that killed NSW woman Krista last week?

image.altText: Rupert Murdoch sitting on a couch with a young boy and a blonde woman

props.synopsis: Lachlan Murdoch was once the reluctant heir apparent to a sprawling media empire, spending years in the wilderness after a confrontation with his father. This is how he was welcomed back into the fold and handed the keys to the kingdom.

title.children: To claim the throne, Lachlan Murdoch gave up his independence and his relationship with his brother

image.altText: A composite image showing an old mental institution and a photo of a young woman against a pink background.

props.synopsis: Alison Watts's grandmother was diagnosed with "puerperal insanity" and institutionalised not long after giving birth to her father. He didn't meet her — or know she was alive — until his early 20s.

title.children: My grandmother Ada spent her life inside mental institutions. I tried to untangle why

image.altText: Caprice Sobel with daughter Isobel and husband Clinton Parker

props.synopsis: Clinton Parker's melanoma is unrelated to sunlight exposure. He's been given just 12 to 24 months to live.

title.children: 'No-one's thinking you can get cancer under your nail': Father's melanoma diagnosed after dropping kettle bell on toe

image.altText: A woman stands smiling.

props.synopsis: Sandra Sully says she once called out the behaviour of a former male colleague after hearing him say a particular journalist's breasts were too large for her role on camera.

title.children: Sandra Sully says the emphasis on her appearance has been 'ridiculous' during her television career

image.altText: A colourful subdivision plan of Narara from 1924

props.synopsis: The State Library of NSW has digitised subdivision plans from as far back as the 1880s and they're not just advertisements. They're works of art.

title.children: Travel back to a time when there was a 'romantic' excitement about new suburbs

image.altText: Pat Cummins throws his son into the air

props.synopsis: At least 14 children travelled with the Australian men's Test side during the recent Ashes series. Here's how the players' young families helped keep them grounded through such a gruelling and dramatic tour.

title.children: The image that sums up the changing dynamic of the Australian men's Test cricket team

image.altText: The sun shines through the clouds over sn open green field of rice crops.

props.synopsis: Rice is agriculture's second-largest methane emitter, surpassing beef, but a small group of growers is producing a rain-fed crop, with a smaller environmental footprint. The problem is they can't export it.

title.children: Farmers want to export 'climate-smart' rice — but an old law stands in their way

image.altText: Castle Bravo nuclear test

props.synopsis: For some, the name "Bikini Bottom" will be synonymous with a pineapple under the sea — the fictional home of SpongeBob SquarePants. But the underwater world of the quirky cartoon character is based on a real place in the Pacific Ocean — and one with a dark history.

title.children: Nuclear bombs vaporised parts of the Bikini Atoll decades ago. What are the lasting impacts today?

image.altText: Photos composite of two kids with their hands up

props.synopsis: The boy and his 11-year-old sister tell police they were driving to California because they were upset their mother had taken away their electronic devices.

title.children: Boy, 10, stopped by police after driving mother's car 320 kilometres across US

image.altText: A man wearing a black jumper smiling at the camera.

props.synopsis: Luke Thomson was known as a confident and outgoing footy coach, so his mates were surprised when he was diagnosed with anxiety and depression.

title.children: Luke hid behind his 'confident' guy persona for years. Then, the dam wall burst

image.altText: the former premier of new south wales gladys berejiklian stands outdoors behind microphones speaking to the media

props.synopsis: In June, the corruption watchdog found Ms Berejiklian had engaged in serious corrupt conduct. At the time her supporters criticised the decision, urging her to appeal.

title.children: Former NSW premier Gladys Berejiklian takes legal action against the ICAC

image.altText: A picture of Hardeep Singh Nijjar wearing a yellow turban and black jacket on a yellow banner.

props.synopsis: Hardeep Singh Nijjar had been warned his life was in danger. But when he walked out of his Sikh temple in Canada, he had no idea two assassins were lying in wait.

title.children: How a brazen assassination confirmed a community's fears and decimated Canada-India relations

image.altText: An Ireland player raises his arms in triumph after Ireland defeated South Africa at the men's Rugby World Cup.

props.synopsis: Mack Hansen, who was born and raised in Canberra, crosses for Ireland's only try, as the number one team in the world takes down the defending champions in a bruising encounter.

title.children: Aussie-born winger helps Ireland to epic win over Springboks at Rugby World Cup

image.altText: A hand holds a phone showing the podcast 'The Nurse', imposed over the images of a hospital and a shadowy man.

props.synopsis: That a paedophile had worked on a children's hospital ward for almost two decades was Launceston's worst kept secret. Then one phone call changed everything, setting in motion a series of events that would alter Tasmania forever.

title.children: 'It started with a phone call': The story behind the hit podcast that exposed a monster

image.altText: An Australian canoe slalom athlete smiles after her run during an event at the 2023 world titles.

props.synopsis: Despite being hit with a two-second time penalty, Australia's Jess Fox triumphs in the women's K1 final at the Canoe Slalom World Championships to add another medal to burgeoning collection.

title.children: Aussie canoeing legend Fox scores 'emotional' victory to claim 14th world title

image.altText: Close up of a man's face in front of a statue of Mary and Jesus

props.synopsis: He still has a beer named after him at a local pub but few people are toasting the career of Bishop Christopher Saunders. It's been a rapid fall from grace for the senior cleric who's accused of sexual assault and appears to be disobeying Vatican orders.

title.children: 'Gone rogue': Surreal scenes in outback Australia as Catholic Church abuse allegations escalate

image.altText: Four polaroid pictures of people with different disabilities in front of a purple background

props.synopsis: As the disability royal commission prepares to hand down its final report, the community has its hopes pinned on recommendations to put an end to the trauma so many still experience, writes Nas Campanella.

title.children: I wasn't surprised by the disability royal commission — what did was the scale at which systems had failed us

image.altText: Thao Tran looking at the camera with tattoos.

props.synopsis: In most Asian cultures, tattoos are viewed as a symbol of gang activity, violence or criminal behaviour. As a result, many children choose to hide their tattoos to avoid conflict with their parents.

title.children: Thao Tran's mum told her that if she ever got a tattoo, she would scrape it off her

image.altText: A woman reads from two parenting books. A pile of more books sits in front of her.

props.synopsis: When you're an exhausted new parent who wants to do the right thing, but not sure what that actually is, it can be hard to stop consulting everything and everyone.

title.children: I have six parenting books and 10 apps. Is there such a thing as too much information?

image.altText: A beekeeper couple standing in amongst bee hives.

props.synopsis: The transition from beehive eradication to management of varroa mite comes as a relief for Kempsey beekeepers who no longer have to euthanase their hives.

title.children: Beehive eradication nearly saw the Costas lose their livelihoods, but this week's decision spares them

image.altText: Lachie Neale smiles and pumps his fist towards the crowd as he leads the Lions off the Gabba

props.synopsis: The grand final awaits the Brisbane Lions after a preliminary final victory over Carlton that was inspired by an unheralded young defender and a unique star recruit. Here are five quick hits.

title.children: Five quick hits — An unlikely hero ignites the Lions as a superstar Blue produces another finals misfire

image.altText: an image of the harbour bridge from 2009 showing the traffic lanes with cars, trains and trucks crossing

props.synopsis: From October 29, drivers will pay $4.27 to use the Sydney Harbour Bridge and Tunnel, a rise of 27 cents from when it last went up in 2009.

title.children: First toll rise in 14 years for Sydney Harbour Bridge and Tunnel 'very moderate', all about 'equity'

image.altText: An NRL player with his fists raised in the air in triumph, smiling to a packed grandstand

props.synopsis: Reece Walsh had his magician's cloak on Saturday night, treating the biggest-ever NRL crowd at Lang Park to a special show that was so impressive the officials missed a blatant forward pass. Here are the five quick hits from the Broncos' victory over the Warriors.

title.children: Five quick hits —  A forward pass can't disguise Reece Walsh's playful magnificence as Broncos reach the grand final

image.altText: A photo of AIsha wearing hijab, in a floral dress, and wearing sunglasses over her scarf.

props.synopsis: For those who follow Islam, wearing a hijab is prescribed for women from puberty. But some women have complicated relationships with the head covering.

title.children: Aisha used to get called 'Osama bin Laden's wife'. She shares what it's like to wear a face covering in Australia

image.altText: A blonde woman sitting at a piano with a young child on her lap who is pressing the keys

props.synopsis: There's a certain subject at school that is music to the ears of its students and the outcomes speak for themselves. Now, finally, teachers are being recognised for the role they play in the lives of music-loving children.

title.children: Teachers have their own category at an awards show and it's about time

image.altText: A man in suit speaks at UN.

props.synopsis: Russia's Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov says Ukraine's proposed peace plan is "not realistic" and accuses the West of direct fighting in Ukraine during his UN speech, as another missile attack hits the city of Sevastopol in Crimea.

title.children: Sergei Lavrov dismisses Ukraine's peace plan and rails against the West, as another missile attack hits Crimea

image.altText: a man wearing swimmers sits on the side of a harbour pool in sydney while looking at this phone

props.synopsis: The ABC's national weather wrap is back, as our meteorologist Tom Saunders breaks down why the declaration of El Niño and a positive Indian Ocean Dipole doesn't guarantee a dry summer.

title.children: El Niño summers show no swing towards wet or dry for majority of Australia

image.altText: Dead wallaby on a roadside

props.synopsis: A one-year trial for roadside posts that emit a high-pitched sound to ward off animals whenever cars approach has concluded, and the results are turning heads.

title.children: Roadkill is up 20pc in NSW, but one council believes its virtual fence offers a solution

image.altText: People take part in a rally against the voice to parliament in Brisbane

props.synopsis: Hundreds of people attend unofficial No vote rallies across Australia ahead of the Voice to Parliament referendum on October 14.

title.children: Protesters gather in major cities, calling for No vote in Voice referendum

image.altText: A Regional Express aeroplane on tarmac.

props.synopsis: Sydney-based specialist who regularly travel to outreach clinics in regional areas say they’re concerned the airline’s decision to reduce flights will put further strain on access specialist care.

title.children: Rex Airlines route cuts spark fears for regional health services

image.altText: Two men hurdle of row of hay bales in front of an old hotel and hundreds of spectators.

props.synopsis: Every two years thousands of visitors arrive in the Queensland town to soak up the outback atmosphere. But some prefer the more hands-on experience of one of the sporting world's more unusual competitions.

title.children: Outback Iron competitors put mettle to the test beneath the blazing Queensland sun
